window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>1","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"INTRODUCTION TO ECONOMICS : BASIC CONCEPT OF ECONOMICS","question":"Economic activities are undertaken to solve the problem of","images":[],"options":{"A":"consumption","B":"opportunity cost","C":"Production","D":"Scarcity"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Economic activities such as production, distribution, and consumption are undertaken to solve the problem of scarcity. Scarcity is a fundamental economic problem of having seemingly unlimited human wants and needs in a world with limited resources. Therefore, societies cannot produce enough to fulfill everyone's wants and needs, leading to the need for economic activities to allocate these scarce resources.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>2","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF PRODUCTION : INTRODUCTION","question":"Farming , mining and fishing are","images":[],"options":{"A":"primary production","B":"Secondary production","C":"Tertiary production","D":"intermediate production"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Farming, mining, and fishing are all examples of primary production. Primary production involves the extraction of raw materials from the earth. This includes agriculture (farming), mining, and fishing. Secondary production involves the transformation of raw materials into finished goods, while tertiary production involves the provision of services.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>3","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF CONSUMER BEHAVIOUR : CONCEPT","question":"A list of consumer's want arranged in order of priority is know as","images":[],"options":{"A":"A budget","B":"an opportunity cost","C":"a scale of preference","D":"choice"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A list of consumer's wants arranged in order of priority is known as a scale of preference. This is a basic economic concept that describes how individuals or societies choose from the limited resources available to them. It involves ranking different options in order of importance to make a choice.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>4","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF CONSUMER BEHAVIOUR : CONSUMER EQUILIBRIUM","question":"The 150.00 naira which olu would have used to purchase a textbook was used to buy a T-shirt.","images":[],"options":{"A":"Olu's real cost is 15.00 naira","B":"Olu opportuity cost costis the T-shirt he bought","C":"Olu's opportunity cost is the text book","D":"Olu's opportunity cost is the T-shirt he bought"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Opportunity cost is a key concept in economics, and it refers to the loss of potential gain from other alternatives when one alternative is chosen. In this case, Olu's opportunity cost is the textbook he could have bought with the 150.00 naira but chose to buy a T-shirt instead.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>5","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF PRODUCTION : FACTORS OF PRODUCTION","question":"The renumeration of the entrepreneur as factor of production is called","images":[],"options":{"A":"wages","B":"salary","C":"interest","D":"profit"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In economics, the remuneration of the entrepreneur as a factor of production is called profit. Profit is the financial gain realized when the amount of revenue gained from a business activity exceeds the expenses, costs, and taxes needed to sustain the activity.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>6","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF PRODUCTION : FACTORS OF PRODUCTION","question":"The production factor , whose entire world supply is fixed is","images":[],"options":{"A":"Land","B":"skilled labour","C":"capital goods","D":"enterpreneurship"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The factor of production whose entire world supply is fixed is Land. This is because the total land area of the earth is fixed and cannot be increased or decreased. Skilled labour, capital goods, and entrepreneurship can all be increased or decreased depending on various factors.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>7","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF PRODUCTION : CONCEPTS OF PRODUCTION","question":"when all factor input are reduced by half , the production possiblity curve will shift","images":[],"options":{"A":"outward","B":"inward","C":"downwards","D":"upwards"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When all factor inputs are reduced by half, the production possibility curve will shift inward. The production possibility curve represents the maximum output possibilities for two goods, given a set of inputs consisting of resources and other factors. When the amount of inputs is reduced, the amount of goods that can be produced also decreases, causing the curve to shift inward.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>8","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"LABOUR MARKET AND UNEMPLOYMENT : INTRODUCTION","question":"When a worker changes from one type of job to another, it is called","images":[],"options":{"A":"geographical mobility of labour","B":"occupatational mobility of labour","C":"immobility of labour","D":"rural-urban"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When a worker changes from one type of job to another, it is called occupational mobility of labour. Occupational mobility refers to the ability of workers to switch career fields in order to find gainful employment or meet labor market needs. Geographical mobility of labour refers to the ability of workers to move from one location to another, while immobility of labour refers to the inability of workers to move from one job or location to another.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>9","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"POPULATION : DETERMINANTS OF POPULATION SIZE","question":"Which of the following determines the size of a country's population ?    I. Birth rate  II. Death rate   III. Migration rate  IV importation   V unemployement","images":[],"options":{"A":"I, II amd V","B":"II and IV","C":"I,  II and III","D":"I and V"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The size of a country's population is determined by the birth rate, death rate, and migration rate. Birth rate refers to the number of live births per 1,000 people per year. Death rate refers to the number of deaths per 1,000 people per year. Migration rate refers to the number of people who move into (immigration) and out of (emigration) a country. Importation and unemployment do not directly determine the size of a country's population.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>10","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"POPULATION : POPULATION STRUCTURE/ DISTRIBUTION","question":"Age distribution is important because it helps the government to","images":[],"options":{"A":"Check rural-urban drift","B":"determines the number of foreigners","C":"Determines the number of factories","D":"undertaken effectively planning"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Age distribution is important for effective planning by the government. It helps the government to understand the demographic structure of the population, which is crucial for planning in areas such as education, healthcare, and social services. It does not directly help in checking rural-urban drift, determining the number of foreigners, or the number of factories.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>11","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"MARKET STRUCTURE : FORMS OF MARKET STRUCTURE","question":"A group of firms producing similar commodities for the same market constitute","images":[],"options":{"A":"cartel","B":"an industry","C":"A co-operative","D":"wholesalers"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A group of firms producing similar commodities for the same market constitute an industry. An industry is a group of companies that are related based on their primary business activities. In modern economies, there are dozens of industry classifications. A cartel is a group of independent market participants who collude with each other in order to improve their profits and dominate the market. A co-operative is an organization owned by the members who use its services or by people who work there. Wholesalers are the entities in the supply chain that buy in bulk and sell to resellers rather than to consumers.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>12","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"INDUSTRY & INDUSTRIALISATION : INTRODUCTION","question":"A factor that has slowed dow the rate of industries deveopment in west Africa is","images":[],"options":{"A":"inadequate techanology","B":"inreasing rate of manpower production","C":"Increased demand for local goods","D":"Intervention of the goverment in business activities"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Inadequate technology can hinder the growth and development of industries.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>13","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF CONSUMER BEHAVIOUR : CONSUMER EQUILIBRIUM","question":"To achieve an equilirbium position , the consumer must buy so much of each commodity whose price is equal to its","images":[],"options":{"A":"marginal utility","B":"diminishing utility","C":"total utility","D":"average utility"},"answer":"A","explanation":"In economics, a consumer is said to be in equilibrium when the price of a commodity is equal to its marginal utility.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>14","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"THE THEORY OF PRICE DETERMINATION : PRICE LEGISLATION","question":"Price control refers to","images":[],"options":{"A":"The ways of making more goods available in the market","B":"a policy of ensuring stable price of ensuring stables price in market","C":"a general redction i price level","D":"effective working of the forces of demand an supply"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Price control refers to government intervention in the market to control the prices of goods and services.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>15","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"INTRODUCTION TO ECONOMICS : BASIC CONCEPT OF ECONOMICS","question":"The desire for goods without the ability to pay is called","images":[],"options":{"A":"choice","B":"effective demand","C":"joint demand","D":"wants"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A want refers to a desire for a good or service, regardless of whether the individual has the ability to pay for it.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>16","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF SUPPLY : MEANING AND DETERMINANTS","question":"Amout of goods offered to market at respective prices and presented i a table is called","images":[],"options":{"A":"price schedule","B":"supply schedule","C":"scale of preference","D":"demand schedule"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A supply schedule is a table that shows the quantity of a good that producers are willing and able to supply at various prices.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>17","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"THE THEORY OF PRICE DETERMINATION : EFFECT OF CHANGE IN SUPPLY & DEMAND ON EQUILIBRIUM PRICE & QUANTITY","question":"At the equilibriumprices , quantity demnded is","images":[],"options":{"A":"greater than quality supplied","B":"equal to quantity supplied","C":"less than quantity","D":"equal to excess supply"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Equilibrium in economics is the state where supply equals demand.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>18","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"THE THEORY OF PRICE DETERMINATION : EFFECT OF CHANGE IN SUPPLY & DEMAND ON EQUILIBRIUM PRICE & QUANTITY","question":"If the government fixed price of commodiy above the equilibrium price, quantity supplied will be","images":[],"options":{"A":"less than quatity demanded","B":"equal to quantity demanded","C":"greater than quantity demanded","D":"equal to zero"},"answer":"C","explanation":"If the government fixed price of a commodity above the equilibrium price, the quantity supplied will be greater than quantity demanded. It is shown in the diagram below;","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>19","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"THE THEORY OF DEMAND : ELASTICITY OF DEMAND","question":"One of the factors determining price elasticity of demand for commodity is the","images":[],"options":{"A":"Availability of close substitutes","B":"number of producer","C":"Government policy","D":"price of other commodity"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The price elasticity of demand for a commodity is determined by several factors, one of which is the availability of close substitutes. If a product has many close substitutes, consumers can easily switch to another product when the price of the original product increases, making the demand for the original product more elastic.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>20","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"THE THEORY OF DEMAND : ELASTICITY OF DEMAND","question":"if elasticity of demand for a commodity is less than one demand is","images":[],"options":{"A":"unitary elasticity","B":"inelasticity","C":"infinitely elastic","D":"zero elastic"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Elasticity of demand measures how much the quantity demanded of a good responds to a change in the price of that good. If the elasticity of demand for a commodity is less than one, it means that the quantity demanded is not very responsive to price changes, which is referred to as inelastic demand.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>21","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"BUSINESS ORGANISATION : PUBLIC CORPORATIONS","question":"The transfer of ownership of a public eneterprise to individual and firms is called","images":[],"options":{"A":"Commercialization","B":"nationalization","C":"privatization","D":"restructuring"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The transfer of ownership of a public enterprise to individuals and firms is called privatization. This process involves the sale of public assets to private owners, often with the aim of increasing efficiency and productivity.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>22","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"BUSINESS ORGANISATION : SOLE PROPRIETOSHIP","question":"One-man businesses are popular in west Africabecause of all the following except the","images":[],"options":{"A":"ease of entry","B":"small capital required","C":"limited entrepreneurial skill needed","D":"tendency to becomes joint-stock companies"},"answer":"D","explanation":"One-man businesses, also known as sole proprietorships, are popular in West Africa due to their ease of entry, small capital requirement, and limited entrepreneurial skill needed. However, they rarely become joint-stock companies. A joint-stock company is a type of business entity where the company's stock is owned jointly by shareholders. This is a more complex business structure that requires more capital, more formalities, and more management skills. Therefore, the tendency to become joint-stock companies is not a reason for the popularity of one-man businesses in West Africa.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>23","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"DISTRIBUTIVE TRADE : THE WHOLESALER","question":"Wholesalers are often criticitized because they","images":[],"options":{"A":"help to break the bulk","B":"finance producers","C":"increase price","D":"provides after-sales services"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Wholesalers are often criticized because they increase prices. Wholesalers buy goods in bulk from manufacturers and sell them in smaller quantities to retailers. The price increase is due to the fact that wholesalers add a markup to the price they paid to the manufacturer to cover their operating costs and to make a profit. The other options are actually benefits of wholesalers: they help to break the bulk (making it easier for retailers to buy in quantities they can handle), they finance producers (by buying in bulk and paying upfront), and they provide after-sales services (such as handling returns).","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>24","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"BUSINESS ORGANISATION : CO-OPERATIVE SOCIETIES","question":"In which of the following business units are the owners mostly the customers?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Co-operative","B":"limited liability companies","C":"partnerships","D":"public corporations"},"answer":"A","explanation":"In co-operative business units, the owners are mostly the customers. A cooperative is a business or organization owned by and operated for the benefit of those using its services. The members, who use the co-op's services, are also its owners. In contrast, in limited liability companies, partnerships, and public corporations, the owners are not necessarily the customers. They are entities or individuals who have invested capital into the business and own shares or stakes in the business.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>25","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"DISTRIBUTIVE TRADE : THE RETAILER","question":"Information about new goods is passed to the buyers through","images":[],"options":{"A":"advertising","B":"retail trade","C":"the manufacturer","D":"wholesaler trade"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Advertising is the primary method through which information about new goods is passed to buyers. It is a marketing communication that employs an openly sponsored, non-personal message to promote or sell a product, service or idea. It is not typically the role of retail trade, the manufacturer, or wholesaler trade to pass information about new goods to buyers, although they may play a part in the process.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>26","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"MARKET STRUCTURE : IMPERFECT MARKET - MONOPOLY","question":"PN equals average revenue or marginal revenue cure of","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"An imperfect competitive firm","B":"a monopoly","C":"a perfectly competitive firm","D":"a monopolistic competitive firm"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The figure PN in the diagram is Average revenue or marginal revenue of a perfect market or perfectly competitive firm.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>27","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"THE CONCEPT OF COST & REVENUE : PROFIT MAXIMIZATION","question":"PN equals average revenue or marginal revenue cure of     The pofit of the producer can be calculated as","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"total cost less total revenue","B":"average revenue less average cost","C":"total revenue less total cost","D":"marginal revenue less marginal cost"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Profit is the total revenue less total cost i.e   Profit = TR = TC","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>28","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"MONEY : INTRODUCTION","question":"The direct exchange of one goods for another without the use of money is known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"Foreign exhange","B":"exchange rate","C":"expenditure","D":"barter"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The direct exchange of one good for another without the use of money is known as barter. Barter is a system of exchange where goods or services are directly exchanged for other goods or services without using a medium of exchange, such as money. It is distinguishable from gift economies in many ways; one of them is that the reciprocal exchange is immediate and not delayed in time.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>29","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"MONEY : CHARACTERISTICS OF MONEY","question":"Acceptability , durability, homogenity , and portability are all attributes of good","images":[],"options":{"A":"markets","B":"money","C":"BANK","D":"government"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Acceptability, durability, homogeneity, and portability are all attributes of good money. Money is any item or verifiable record that is generally accepted as payment for goods and services and repayment of debts, such as taxes, in a particular country or socio-economic context. The main functions of money are distinguished as: a medium of exchange, a unit of account, a store of value and sometimes, a standard of deferred payment.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>30","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"MONEY : DEMAND FOR MONEY","question":"The term demand for money means","images":[],"options":{"A":"desire to borrow money from people","B":"desire of a individual to invest all his money projects","C":"willingness of people to hold money","D":"willingness of people to keep"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The term 'demand for money' in economics refers to the total amount of money that all sectors in the economy would like to hold in liquid form. This is not about borrowing or investing money, but about the willingness to hold money. Therefore, the correct answer is 'willingness of people to hold money'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>31","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"INFLATION & DEFLATION : INTRODUCTION","question":"A persistent and appreciate rise in the general level of prices is known  as","images":[],"options":{"A":"depreciation","B":"inflation","C":"deflation","D":"production"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A persistent and appreciable rise in the general level of prices is known as inflation. Inflation is a measure of the rate of price increases in an economy over a period of time. It is not depreciation, deflation, or production. Therefore, the correct answer is 'inflation'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>32","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"FINANCIAL INSTITUTION : COMMERCIAL BANKS","question":"To a commercial bank , deposits are","images":[],"options":{"A":"liabilities","B":"assets","C":"capital","D":"production"},"answer":"A","explanation":"In the balance sheet of a commercial bank, deposits are considered as liabilities. This is because the bank is obliged to return the money to the depositors on demand or after a certain period. Therefore, the correct answer is 'liability'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>33","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"FINANCIAL INSTITUTION : CENTRAL BANK","question":"The lender of last resort in the banking system is he","images":[],"options":{"A":"industrial bank","B":"mortgage bank","C":"commercial bank","D":"central bank"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The Central Bank is known as the lender of last resort in the banking system. This is because it provides financial support to banks or financial institutions facing financial difficulties. The Central Bank can lend money to these institutions to prevent their collapse, which could have a negative impact on the economy.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>34","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"FINANCIAL INSTITUTION : CHEQUES","question":"Discounting a bill of exchange means the bill is","images":[],"options":{"A":"cash over the counter","B":"sold on the stock exchange","C":"bought for less than its face value","D":"Sold to the highest"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Discounting a bill of exchange means buying it for less than its face value. The difference between the face value of the bill and its purchase price is the 'discount'. This is a common practice in finance where a bill of exchange is sold before its maturity date for a price less than its face value.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>35","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"FINANCIAL INSTITUTION : CENTRAL BANK","question":"the central bank control credit in the economy through the use of","images":[],"options":{"A":"legal tender","B":"travellers cheques","C":"foreign exchange instrument","D":"open market operation"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The Central Bank controls credit in the economy through the use of open market operations. Open market operations involve the buying and selling of government securities in the open market in order to expand or contract the amount of money in the banking system. By doing so, the Central Bank can influence interest rates and control credit in the economy.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>36","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : PRINCIPLE OF TAXATION","question":"Among principles of taxation propounded by Adam smith was that","images":[],"options":{"A":"a tax should be impossible to evade","B":"a tax should be convenient to pay","C":"no tax should be levied on food","D":"there should be no taxation without representation"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Adam Smith, a renowned economist, proposed four principles of taxation, one of which is that taxes should be convenient to pay. This principle states that a tax should be levied at the time and in the manner in which it is most likely to be convenient for the contributor to pay it. None of the other options align with Adam Smith's principles of taxation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>37","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : CLASSIFICATION OF TAX","question":"Mr. Bala's income is $800.00 per month while that mr jatau is $1200.00 if messres, Bala and jatau paid $80 and $120.00 repectively as taxes the tax system is","images":[],"options":{"A":"progressive","B":"regressive","C":"proportional","D":"ad-valorem"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The tax system described in the question is proportional. In a proportional tax system, all taxpayers pay the same percentage of their income, regardless of the actual amount of income. In this case, both Mr. Bala and Mr. Jatau are paying 10% of their income as tax ($80/$800 = 10% and $120/$1200 = 10%), which is characteristic of a proportional tax system.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>38","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"AGRICULTURE IN WEST AFRICA : MARKETING BOARDS","question":"Government revenue from the groundnut industry is from","images":[],"options":{"A":"licenses","B":"rent","C":"royalties","D":"taxes"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Government revenue from industries such as the groundnut industry is typically derived from taxes. These taxes can be levied on the income or profits of the industry, or on the goods and services it produces. Licenses, rent, and royalties can also provide revenue, but these are not the primary sources of government revenue from industries.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>39","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"INTERNATIONAL TRADE : PRINCIPLES OF INTERNATIONAL TRADE","question":"The theory of comparative cost advvantage is associated with","images":[],"options":{"A":"Alfred marshal","B":"Adam smith","C":"David Ricado","D":"J.B . Say"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The theory of comparative cost advantage is associated with David Ricardo. This theory states that a country should specialize in producing and exporting only those goods and services which it can produce more efficiently (at a lower opportunity cost) than other goods and services (which it should import).","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>40","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"INTERNATIONAL TRADE : BALANCE OF TRADE & PAYMENT","question":"When the value of a nation's exports is greater than its imports","images":[],"options":{"A":"a favourable balance balance of trade exists","B":"an unfavourable balance of payment exists","C":"The net foreig trade is zero","D":"inflation occurs"},"answer":"A","explanation":"When the value of a nation's exports is greater than its imports, a favourable balance of trade exists. This is because the country is earning more from its exports than it is spending on imports, which is generally seen as a positive economic situation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>41","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"INTERNATIONAL TRADE : BALANCE OF TRADE & PAYMENT","question":"To improve the balance of payment position of west African countries , there must be","images":[],"options":{"A":"removal of barriers to improtation of goods and services","B":"increase rate of exportation of goods and services","C":"increase domestic consumption of foriegn produced goods","D":"the development of the local market"},"answer":"B","explanation":"To improve the balance of payment position of West African countries, there must be an increase in the rate of exportation of goods and services. The balance of payments is a record of all economic transactions between the residents of a country and the rest of the world. It is improved by increasing exports, which brings more foreign currency into the country, or by reducing imports, which sends less currency out of the country.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>42","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"ECONOMIC INTEGRATION : OBJECTIVES, LEVELS OF AND FEATURES","question":"The economic community of West African states (ECOWAS) is an examle of","images":[],"options":{"A":"bilateral trade","B":"Economic integration","C":"regional marketin board","D":"international competition"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) is an example of economic integration. Economic integration is an arrangement among nations that typically includes the reduction or elimination of trade barriers and the coordination of monetary and fiscal policies. ECOWAS, established in 1975, is a regional group of fifteen West African countries, designed to promote economic integration across the region.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>43","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"AGRICULTURE IN WEST AFRICA : INTRODUCTION","question":"One reason for the low agricultural production in west Africa countries is that","images":[],"options":{"A":"agricultural employs the highest percentage of labour force","B":"Too much money is invested in agriculture","C":"farmers lack the finance and technology required","D":"farm are too large"},"answer":"C","explanation":"One reason for the low agricultural production in West African countries is that farmers lack the finance and technology required. Agriculture in many West African countries is often characterized by low productivity due to factors such as lack of access to finance, inadequate technology, poor infrastructure, and lack of modern farming techniques.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>44","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"ECONOMIC SYSTEM : ECONOMIC PROBLEMS OF THE SOCIETY","question":"Mono-product economies are those that","images":[],"options":{"A":"Produce one main commodity","B":"produce only raw materials","C":"depends on export of their raw materials","D":"specialize in agricultural industries"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Mono-product economies are those that produce one main commodity. These economies are heavily dependent on the production and export of a single commodity, which often makes them vulnerable to price fluctuations and economic instability. Examples of such economies include oil in Saudi Arabia and Nigeria, and diamonds in Botswana.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>45","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"MARKET STRUCTURE : MEANING OF MARKET & TYPES","question":"An essentials charateristics of a market economy is","images":[],"options":{"A":"goverment control","B":"producer surplus","C":"consumer surplus","D":"Consumer Sovereignty"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A market economy is characterized by consumer sovereignty. This means that the production and distribution of goods and services are guided by the aggregate interactions of a community's citizens. In other words, the consumers determine what goods and services are produced based on their demands. Therefore, the correct answer is 'Consumer Sovereignty'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>46","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"ECONOMIC SYSTEM : TYPES AND FEATURES OF ECONOMIC SYSTEM","question":"In a capitalist  system goods are produced for those who","images":[],"options":{"A":"want them most but cannot pay for them","B":"can pay for them but do not want them","C":"want them and can also pay for them","D":"are dependent on the labout force"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In a capitalist system, goods are produced for those who want them and can also pay for them. This is because capitalism is an economic system where private entities own the factors of production. The four factors are entrepreneurship, capital goods, natural resources, and labor. The owners of these resources compete with one another over consumers, who in turn, pay to utilize them. Therefore, the correct answer is 'want them and can also pay for them'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>47","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"ECONOMIC SYSTEM : TYPES AND FEATURES OF ECONOMIC SYSTEM","question":"An economy which exibits features of a both private and state enterprises is known as a","images":[],"options":{"A":"capitalist economy","B":"mixed economy","C":"communist economy","D":"socialist economy"},"answer":"B","explanation":"An economy that exhibits features of both private and state enterprises is known as a mixed economy. This is because a mixed economy is a system that combines aspects of both capitalism and socialism. It includes a variety of public and government control, as well as economic planning. Therefore, the correct answer is 'mixed economy'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>48","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"NATIONAL INCOME : CONCEPT","question":"In calculating the national income of a country X, the cost of both raw materials and the finished products were included . This is a case of","images":[],"options":{"A":"double counting","B":"price fluntuation","C":"price differentiation","D":"price discrimination"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The inclusion of both the cost of raw materials and the finished products in the calculation of a country's national income is a case of double counting. Double counting in economics refers to the error of counting the same costs or benefits more than once in the process of economic calculation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>49","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"ECONOMIC GROWTH AND DEVELOPMENT : DEVELOPMENT PLANNING","question":"Economic development is defined as","images":[],"options":{"A":"outward shift of the production possibility curve","B":"availability of more goods and services","C":"Growth accompanied by qualitative in living standards","D":"Growth in the national income"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Economic development is defined as growth accompanied by qualitative improvement in living standards. It is not just about the availability of more goods and services or growth in the national income, but also about the improvement in the quality of life, which includes factors like health, education, and equality of opportunity.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2005>50","subject":"Economics","year":"2005","type":"Objective","topic":"MAJOR NATURAL RESOURCES : OPEC","question":"Which of the following is not an objective of the organisation of the petroluem exporting countries(OPEC)?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Stabilization of oil prices","B":"co-ordinating prices","C":"Harmonizing oil prices","D":"stagnation of developed economies"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The objectives of the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) include the stabilization, coordination, and harmonization of oil prices. However, causing stagnation of developed economies is not an objective of OPEC. OPEC's mission is to coordinate and unify the petroleum policies of its Member Countries and ensure the stabilization of oil markets in order to secure an efficient, economic and regular supply of petroleum to consumers, a steady income to producers and a fair return on capital for those investing in the petroleum industry.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"}];